prj:TechnicalJustification.prj:justificationText: We request a spatial resolution of 1.4 arcsec for this continuum detection experiment. The majority of the sources in our sample should remain basically unresolved. We aim to obtain a sensitivity of 0.14mJy rms in the continuum for all of the sources. This will result in S/N>5 detections of sources with SFR>100Msun/yr, ~30% individual detections at S/N>3 of our sample. Our primary aim is to obtain statistical detections by stacking subsamples of the galaxies observed with ALMA. Our chosen spectral resolution will correspond to 25 km/s, for a 2GHz (1600km/s) bandwidth, fully appropriate for this project and further enabling us to search for emission lines (for some of our targets that may have high-J CO8-7 or 7-6 transitions falling into the ALMA band). We need all 4 basebands to measure the continuum.
We use four basebands, each of 1.875 GHz in width, to maximize our detection of the continuum centered at the rest-frame wavelength of 850um for all of our targets.

We have specified an angular resolution larger than 1 arcsec so that we can measure the total CO flux for our targets and not resolve out any of the emission if observed at higher spatial resolution. The largest angular resolution should be 4 arcsec since our targets can have nearby sources (i.e., possibly in galaxy mergers) that can suffer from blending issues if observed on larger scales.

prp:ObsProposal.prp:abstract: We propose to measure dust mass for a unique sample of 156 star-forming galaxies at z~1.6 with direct metallicity information from our Subaru/FMOS NIR spectroscopy. This will be achieved by measuring the 850um continuum flux in ALMA band 7. For all galaxies, we have individual Halpha detections and coverage of the optical emission lines including Hbeta, [NII] and [OIII], from which we have derived gas phase metallicities, reddening through Balmer decrement thus dust-corrected SFRs when stacking subsamples of ~15 galaxies. ALMA observations will provide individual detections for ~30% of the sample while stacking will deliver a direct estimate of the dust mass across the full population. With metallicity measurements in hand, we will be able to convert Mdust into total Mgas (independently of the alpha_CO ratio) for the first time at this redshift, while doing so with a reliable estimate of the gas-to-dust ratio. Together with the already measured stellar masses, SFRs and metallicities, dust and gas masses, we will complete a set of fundamental global parameters necessary to characterize galaxies at these redshifts and further enable us to explore their inter-relations.
